17:13.511 --> 17:14.232
Here's another one.

17:14.252 --> 17:15.493
This one isn't even bound.

17:16.174 --> 17:20.179
You can see this is what the Library of Congress did to mark their deaccessioning.

17:21.421 --> 17:26.287
And it's just a little story with the Library of Congress call numbers.

17:26.307 --> 17:28.170
And they found their way into my collection.

17:28.670 --> 17:31.414
And then I have one book.

17:32.272 --> 17:34.414
which is the only known book of its kind.

17:34.854 --> 17:37.056
Who picks the fabric for the boxes?

17:37.156 --> 17:37.296
I do.

17:37.317 --> 17:38.898
No, I do that.

17:39.999 --> 17:40.179
Right.

17:40.519 --> 17:42.881
Well, what makes you decide that you want a certain... I don't know.

17:43.002 --> 17:51.990
I suggest to him what kind of book I'd like to have, and then he does the boxes.

17:52.010 --> 17:53.131
These are little parodies.

17:53.151 --> 17:54.452
I love parodies of Holmes.

17:55.132 --> 17:56.534
He's had millions of parodies.

17:57.074 --> 17:57.895
This one is great.

17:59.076 --> 18:01.418
This is the Sleuths, and it contains...

18:01.617 --> 18:06.963
And this is the original Library of Congress deposit card for this.

18:07.724 --> 18:09.707
And I bought this at auction in New York.

18:09.727 --> 18:15.714
And I had to buy the whole set of these to get this one throughout the rest of the set, which had no value.

18:16.214 --> 18:17.295
And this one is incredible.

18:18.677 --> 18:19.798
And here's a pick-lock hole.

18:19.919 --> 18:21.681
Here's another one of Dan's parodies.

18:22.462 --> 18:24.684
This one was written on an exhibition at Harvard.

18:24.784 --> 18:26.406
The Adventures of... Pick-lock Holes.

18:26.546 --> 18:27.928
These are incredibly rare.

18:28.837 --> 18:35.986
But these are even rarer than most copies, because they're all inscribed.

18:37.729 --> 18:38.870
I mean, these are just unheard of.

18:41.073 --> 18:46.720
Look at the condition of the book, too.

18:48.322 --> 18:51.446
That's the author's granddaughter, Martha Peabody.

18:51.466 --> 18:52.147
Could you read it?

18:52.167 --> 18:54.010
It's Martha Peabody from R.C.

18:54.050 --> 18:56.633
Layman, Xmas, 1901.

18:57.052 --> 19:02.817
And I've never heard in all the years of my collection of any other inscribed copies.

19:05.219 --> 19:07.221
That's one of the parodies there.

19:07.241 --> 19:08.062
Except this one.

19:09.603 --> 19:12.125
So there are two inscribed copies in the world.

19:12.285 --> 19:13.847
And I have them both.

19:14.187 --> 19:14.647
Two known.

19:14.908 --> 19:15.548
Two known ones.

19:15.889 --> 19:17.110
Rosamond P. Byron's sister.

19:17.130 --> 19:18.150
Don't ever say they were only two.

19:18.171 --> 19:18.751
Two known, two known.

19:18.771 --> 19:20.533
It's like they're only 10 Tamerlanes.

19:20.713 --> 19:21.694
Only two known.

19:21.854 --> 19:23.195
And then the 12th, right?

19:23.235 --> 19:26.738
This is a birthday present that I got for Danny.

19:26.937 --> 19:28.679
Ralph Sipper turned this up.

19:31.022 --> 19:34.706
Now, I also collect the rarest detective fiction, okay?

19:34.726 --> 19:36.108
He collects Queen's Quorum titles.

19:36.288 --> 19:36.508
Right.

19:38.331 --> 19:44.558
Dan already had this book in his collection, but the copy that he had was not nearly as beautiful as this one.

19:44.578 --> 19:53.228
I bought this book, not this particular one, but I bought my first copy from Lou Feldman, and I paid, I think, $100 from Lou Feldman.

19:53.268 --> 19:54.750
It was from the K collection.

19:55.253 --> 20:04.429
And that was the only copy I saw for years, until Priscilla turned this copy up at Ralph Zipper's, and she bought it for me for a birthday present.

20:04.449 --> 20:09.617
The same thing, these books are all great detective fiction.

20:09.637 --> 20:10.679
This one is incredible.

20:10.719 --> 20:12.783
Look at the jacket on this.

20:15.347 --> 20:21.177
This is the Queen's Quorum title, too, and this one has a nice sign by the author, Thomas Burke.

20:23.401 --> 20:28.767
I mean, is there a better collection than this, in your own humble opinion, of this?

20:29.067 --> 20:35.313
Well, of Sherlock Holmes, in book and in letters, there isn't any.

20:36.835 --> 20:37.075
Okay?

20:37.095 --> 20:38.417
This is a preeminent collection.

20:38.737 --> 20:38.997
Right.

20:39.658 --> 20:44.063
I think that most people, well, most people would agree if they saw it.

20:44.443 --> 20:48.227
Remember, there have probably been two people that have seen this collection.

20:48.832 --> 20:49.433
to see that.

20:49.493 --> 20:50.494
I'm so privileged.

20:50.534 --> 20:52.357
I really... No, don't feel privileged.

20:52.437 --> 20:54.360
I do, because... It's not my thing.

20:54.460 --> 21:00.568
I just haven't... You're interested, so I'm enthusiastic about it, and I'm very happy... Do you have a catalog?

21:00.588 --> 21:01.089
No.

21:01.109 --> 21:02.491
I'm in the process of cataloging.

21:02.511 --> 21:04.333
You should catalog it.

21:04.353 --> 21:06.476
What is it that's about?

21:06.836 --> 21:07.918
That's there someplace.

21:08.839 --> 21:10.401
No, it's on the other one.

21:10.421 --> 21:12.344
Over there?

21:12.364 --> 21:13.205
Yeah.

21:13.225 --> 21:14.787
Is it under the... Yeah.

21:14.807 --> 21:16.490
Now, here are some great books.

21:16.510 --> 21:16.830
I mean,

21:17.333 --> 21:28.469
If you remember at the fair, Mark Hyman, a dealer from California, had a couple of Sherlock Holmes books.

21:28.489 --> 21:31.934
These are the first and second issues of The Sign of the Four.

21:33.076 --> 21:34.698
Now, the thing about this is condition.

21:38.423 --> 21:42.970
Now, Mark's book, which he sold at the fair for $13,500,

21:43.186 --> 21:46.830
was not nearly, didn't even begin to compare with this copy.

21:46.890 --> 21:48.412
This is the finest known copy.

21:48.432 --> 21:49.694
There's no question about it.

21:52.557 --> 21:55.881
Oh, I'll find it for you.

21:55.901 --> 21:56.562
One second.

21:56.842 --> 21:58.724
And I love condition.

21:58.804 --> 22:07.334
And so I've made a real passion of finding these books in great condition.

22:07.895 --> 22:08.976
This is another single.

22:09.036 --> 22:10.358
My God.

22:10.490 --> 22:13.334
This is the White Company, a novel in a three-decker by Doyle.

22:13.754 --> 22:15.016
He's 19th century.

22:15.477 --> 22:21.885
And you say these were all issued with jackets, even if they were plain wrappers.

22:21.905 --> 22:23.468
Well, the three-decker one wasn't.

22:23.488 --> 22:25.250
This one was probably issued in a jacket.

22:25.270 --> 22:28.014
Do you think it had anything pictorial on it, or was it just a plain wrapper?

22:28.034 --> 22:28.655
I don't think this one did.

22:29.416 --> 22:33.381
Some did, but I don't believe that this one did.

22:33.401 --> 22:36.345
And then, you know, I'm sort of working my way towards...

22:37.827 --> 22:41.493
the cornerstones of the collections, which is what we're getting to.

22:42.254 --> 22:44.938
Quite literally, we're on the upper shelf, moving left.

22:45.118 --> 22:48.323
And I skipped a whole lot of stuff in here, a lot of great stuff.

22:49.224 --> 22:54.292
But The Sign of the Floor, that's the first legitimate issue in England.

22:54.552 --> 23:01.082
But there was a previous issue that was published in the United States in a pirate edition, which is impossible to find.

23:01.503 --> 23:05.189
And this one is incredibly rare, especially because of the condition.

23:05.209 --> 23:06.771
It has the complete back strip.

23:07.173 --> 23:13.940
And when you get into this rarefied atmosphere, the backstrip is really important because it's the first thing that goes, believe it or not.

23:14.061 --> 23:14.581
I know that.

23:14.821 --> 23:23.050
So the difference between this copy and a lesser one with no backstrip is like $8,000 difference just for the backstrip.

23:23.091 --> 23:24.052
Published by Collier.

23:24.172 --> 23:24.472
Exactly.

23:24.492 --> 23:25.573
That's the same guy.

23:25.593 --> 23:26.634
That's the same Collier.

23:26.674 --> 23:27.896
It's 1891.

23:28.016 --> 23:28.416
Right.

23:28.436 --> 23:32.120
Exactly.

23:32.321 --> 23:37.146
And then just working our way down, this is the first book edition.

23:38.864 --> 23:41.167
of A Study in Scarlet, which is the first book.

23:44.791 --> 23:48.356
This is the English style, by the way, of box making.

23:48.376 --> 23:51.380
You see, it's a totally different style.

23:51.400 --> 23:53.642
Do you have why they're getting this open?

23:53.662 --> 23:55.284
Do you have any of Doyle's own books?

23:56.105 --> 23:57.487
No, I don't.

23:58.188 --> 24:03.875
And there was a collection of Doyle's own books, but not Sherlock Holmes, and I was not interested in those.

24:03.935 --> 24:05.097
I do have a few, actually.

24:05.597 --> 24:06.018
Yeah, I do.

24:06.218 --> 24:08.601
You're not interested in any of his non-Sherlock Holmes books?

24:09.121 --> 24:11.945
Oh, I am, but I mean, do I have a book?

24:11.965 --> 24:13.567
That was the question.

24:13.587 --> 24:15.070
Oh, I do, yeah, I do.

24:15.190 --> 24:17.994
Do you want to know about the current book plate?

24:18.014 --> 24:19.456
This is an incredible thing.

24:20.317 --> 24:23.802
And that condition for that book, again, it's the finest known product.

24:23.842 --> 24:26.546
Now, is this, what is this, a little mildew there?

24:26.766 --> 24:29.911
Foxing, exactly the way it came, and it's exactly, it's been like that.

24:29.931 --> 24:31.072
Have you treated it?

24:31.092 --> 24:35.719
No, it's been like that since probably 20 years after it was issued.

24:39.395 --> 24:44.143
That's an incredible book.

24:44.804 --> 24:45.926
How long have you had that?

24:46.447 --> 24:47.929
Three or four years.

24:48.670 --> 24:49.752
So you're still working on this.

24:50.053 --> 24:51.615
This is a very active collection.

24:51.635 --> 24:55.362
This is a live, completely live collection.

24:55.382 --> 24:57.445
This is the cornerstone of any collection.

24:57.645 --> 25:01.792
Not necessarily the most valuable book, but very valuable.

25:02.834 --> 25:04.677
But this is the Beaton's Christmas Angle.

25:05.618 --> 25:07.461
And this is the most photographed book.

25:07.481 --> 25:08.983
I mean, Priscilla can show you a T-shirt.

25:09.003 --> 25:09.845
Study in Scarlet.

25:09.885 --> 25:10.586
Which I did.

25:11.467 --> 25:14.092
And this is the first appearance of Holmes in print.

25:15.153 --> 25:17.277
And this is all that's left of this back strip.

25:17.417 --> 25:18.719
The A is missing.

25:20.161 --> 25:20.943
It's intact.

25:20.963 --> 25:21.824
But it's intact.

25:21.844 --> 25:23.647
And this is one of the finest copies now.

25:24.468 --> 25:26.952
Not the finest, but one of the finest.

25:26.972 --> 25:28.154
And you acquired that where?

25:28.715 --> 25:31.840
And I acquired that about two or three years ago.

25:31.860 --> 25:32.201
Wow.

25:32.221 --> 25:32.301
Wow.

25:33.479 --> 25:41.046
Is this opportunity, I mean, are these just things that you've just found within the last two or three years, or are things that you've just been able to afford in the last two or three years?

25:41.347 --> 25:44.129
Well, affording is part of it, but some of these have not appeared.

25:45.010 --> 25:46.412
And the collection goes way back.

25:46.612 --> 25:48.494
This collection goes back 35 years.

25:49.154 --> 25:53.699
So some of these, for instance, this Valley of Fear that I showed you is a rather old book.

25:53.719 --> 25:57.823
These adventures and memoirs, the first edition of the adventures, first edition of the memoirs, are old.

25:58.343 --> 25:59.845
These are inscribed by Doyle.

26:00.505 --> 26:01.326
These are old.

26:01.913 --> 26:06.519
I haven't shown you a lot of things, but... Well, what do you really covet?

26:06.599 --> 26:07.199
It's not here.

26:07.340 --> 26:08.941
I mean, two or three years.

26:08.961 --> 26:10.103
You said the living collection.

26:10.383 --> 26:11.164
Not covet.

26:11.184 --> 26:14.668
That's the wrong word, but... Let's put it this way.

26:14.688 --> 26:17.712
When you go to a big fair like New York or something in London, what are you looking for?

26:17.772 --> 26:18.973
Then I look for parodies.

26:19.114 --> 26:21.456
The only thing I can find there are parodies.

26:21.577 --> 26:23.699
I love parodies of Holmes.

26:23.779 --> 26:26.082
Sherlock Holmes, Sherlock Holmes.

26:26.500 --> 26:28.242
They're very rare in themselves.

26:28.422 --> 26:29.384
These are all parodies.

26:29.404 --> 26:31.506
This is a parody, The Eleven Tough Buttons.

26:31.586 --> 26:37.934
Here's a whole book of parodies and misadventures, spooks, misfits, the sleuths, Carrington's Cases.

26:37.974 --> 26:44.302
I mean, if you want to see condition for a book, I mean, this is just incredible for this particular book.

26:44.322 --> 26:44.822
Carrington's Cases, yeah.

26:45.423 --> 26:47.606
And it has a homeless parody in it.

26:47.626 --> 26:52.231
And these are very, they're not only collectible, but they're very difficult to find.

26:52.251 --> 26:55.275
And, of course, they're worth a lot of money.

26:56.538 --> 27:02.107
So in terms of the core collection, the A-Adams, you pretty well have the whole shelf on them.

27:02.127 --> 27:02.868
I have the whole shelf.

27:03.069 --> 27:03.569
Yeah.

27:03.589 --> 27:03.990
Right.

27:04.010 --> 27:06.574
I'm still looking for a little thing to fill in here and there.

27:06.995 --> 27:10.721
I'm always upgrading in terms of condition constantly.

27:11.382 --> 27:18.794
But here's a book like this, the first American edition of The Hound of the Baskervilles, the first true American edition, which is a very scarce book.

27:18.814 --> 27:20.917
I'm still looking for that in jacket.

27:20.937 --> 27:21.598
Okay?

27:21.618 --> 27:23.862
Here's a book that I got recently in jacket.

27:24.415 --> 27:28.300
This is the only known copy in a jacket, The Return of Sherlock Holmes.

27:28.520 --> 27:29.461
It's a late book.

27:29.481 --> 27:33.467
It's 1905, and it is the only known copy in a jacket.

27:33.487 --> 27:34.027
From a dealer?

27:34.728 --> 27:35.649
From a dealer, right.

27:35.669 --> 27:37.572
Do you remember what you thought when you saw it?

27:38.112 --> 27:39.254
Yeah, I went wild.

27:39.274 --> 27:39.935
I think it fell.

27:42.158 --> 27:44.841
Did you see it in the catalog, or did you just kind of walk into a shop?

27:45.482 --> 27:47.164
People know what I collect.

27:47.805 --> 27:48.386
Here's a book.

27:48.446 --> 27:50.288
I mean, you want to talk about a book?

27:50.622 --> 27:52.464
The dealer is an odd book.

27:52.484 --> 27:54.465
Take advantage of that kind of obsession, though.

27:54.485 --> 27:56.807
Sometimes, yeah.

27:57.047 --> 27:57.668
But you know what?

27:58.168 --> 27:58.629
You know what?

27:59.129 --> 28:01.291
My position is I always know more than the dealer.

28:02.552 --> 28:08.177
So if I buy a book and I pay for it, if it's in my field, I'm going to get the better of the deal.

28:08.897 --> 28:09.658
Well, you've got the book.

28:09.678 --> 28:13.821
But the dealer never knows what the real value is, and I've got the book.

28:13.841 --> 28:14.342
Exactly.

28:15.483 --> 28:16.784
This is a wonderful story.

28:16.844 --> 28:20.427
This is a book full of Doyle letters.

28:20.795 --> 28:23.920
Now that says My Dear Watson, but it's not My Dear Watson.

28:24.360 --> 28:26.884
These are all Doyle materials and Doyle letters.

28:27.765 --> 28:30.028
Here's Arthur Conan Doyle and his son.

28:30.108 --> 28:31.851
Isn't that wonderful?

28:35.396 --> 28:37.119
That's Doyle at the end of his life.

28:37.599 --> 28:40.003
That's his inscription, life's pilgrimage.

28:40.844 --> 28:43.428
Let me read you this letter.

28:44.229 --> 28:45.190
This comes from Rhoda.

28:46.873 --> 28:48.976
I'm going to see Anthony.

28:49.036 --> 28:50.498
This is dated November

28:51.220 --> 28:52.661
21st, 1940.

28:52.781 --> 28:57.906
Temporary address, and I'll tell you why in a minute, 8 Burlington Gardens.

28:58.807 --> 29:01.910
My dear mister, and I won't repeat the name because I don't want to mention it.

29:02.450 --> 29:11.619
Very many thanks for your cabled order of October 30th for the Doyle album and cobbler's campaigning, and for your confirmatory letter of November 1st just received.

29:12.119 --> 29:18.645
The reason why the Doyle item was not sent immediately is that it suffered slightly in the bombing of Bodley House.

29:19.098 --> 29:21.200
The cloth binding was lightly stained.

29:22.021 --> 29:24.063
Fortunately, the contents came to no harm.

29:24.643 --> 29:34.813
I wanted to keep the volume back for inspection by the insurance law's assessors, but as it seems that they may not be here for weeks yet, I think I had better send you the item at once.

29:35.294 --> 29:46.084
I thought of having it rebound in the same style, but then I thought, you might not find it uninteresting to have in your library one book which bears the honorable scars of the Battle of Britain.

29:46.958 --> 29:50.322
And I thought that letter, to me, this is in value.

29:50.382 --> 29:51.683
It's not that great in value.

29:51.844 --> 29:56.449
But to have that book, it just gives you a wonderful feeling.

29:57.650 --> 29:59.693
You know, I've heard this all of them.

29:59.713 --> 30:03.577
A very dear friend of mine, now deceased, who actually started me as a book collector.

30:03.637 --> 30:04.718
He used to be the music critic.

30:06.200 --> 30:06.761
He had that.

30:06.781 --> 30:08.002
He played it for me one night.

30:08.022 --> 30:12.287
And it is arguably the funniest thing I've ever heard in my life.

30:13.128 --> 30:13.989
Have you seen this one?

30:14.129 --> 30:15.731
This is a gift from Peter Stern.

30:15.911 --> 30:16.712
Peter Stern.

30:17.317 --> 30:27.631
One of the things which are also touching, these are World War I journals, prisoner of war camp journals.

30:27.651 --> 30:28.873
The camp was Ruhleben.

30:29.934 --> 30:31.556
R-U-H-L.

30:32.878 --> 30:33.178
L-E-B-E-N.

30:33.719 --> 30:37.144
And it was a very famous prisoner of war camp where the British were held prisoner.

30:37.284 --> 30:37.744
Infamous.

30:37.845 --> 30:42.311
And it was a huge camp, probably 25,000 people in the camp.

30:42.511 --> 30:43.392
Ran for miles.

30:43.709 --> 30:48.276
And they developed their own colleges and their own universities within the camp.

30:48.296 --> 30:51.841
And they put on all these various shows.

30:52.482 --> 30:54.766
And, of course, there's quite a bit about Holmes.

30:56.248 --> 30:58.812
Here's The Speckled Band by A. Conan Doyle.

30:59.252 --> 31:01.716
So the whole thing is full of material on Sherlock Holmes.

31:02.357 --> 31:10.189
What makes this so interesting is this copy was bound by someone in the camp and sent back home.

31:11.941 --> 31:15.985
This is to who it was sent, and he was the binder, Ernest Long.

31:17.446 --> 31:21.250
And again, this is the only known copy in a camp binding.

31:21.951 --> 31:22.892
They set up a bindery.

31:22.952 --> 31:26.315
And you've marked these pages for it, because those are where the Holmes things are.

31:26.335 --> 31:27.476
Yeah, exactly.

31:27.496 --> 31:32.101
This is the little binder's ticket right here to be sent to.

31:34.423 --> 31:36.986
And here's a copy that is bound in a regular binding.

31:37.626 --> 31:38.127
Same thing.

31:38.147 --> 31:41.290
But it's very scarce to begin with.

31:42.839 --> 31:48.567
Then you have to buy some copies from his own collection.

31:48.588 --> 31:50.631
I'll just show you.

31:50.651 --> 31:52.093
A collection, a library, I guess.

31:52.113 --> 31:52.513
Library.

31:52.533 --> 31:56.800
Let's see if I can find something.

31:56.860 --> 31:57.781
You don't have to show me.

31:57.881 --> 31:59.964
I was just curious if you had any.

31:59.984 --> 32:04.611
Well, they're interesting because they have his notations on it.

32:04.631 --> 32:06.614
Are the slippers anything, or are they just slippers?

32:08.437 --> 32:10.500
Well, he kept his tobacco.

32:10.987 --> 32:13.130
He kept his tobacco when the person slipped.

32:13.150 --> 32:15.354
I figured it had to have reason to be on that show.

32:15.554 --> 32:22.604
This is a wonderful finding, again, done by the critics.

32:22.945 --> 32:29.515
It's a book that I had been looking for for years called How to Do It, a Sherlock Holmes parody.

32:30.136 --> 32:37.146
Again, because I'm such a condition freak, it's a great condition jacket and has a shark on the parody.

32:38.408 --> 32:43.174
It's got a little statue, a little, we can call it a statue, we would call it.

32:43.295 --> 32:44.436
A little leather holmes on the spine.

32:44.456 --> 32:52.768
A little leather holmes on the spine, which I've never seen anything quite like it before.

32:52.788 --> 32:59.376
Some of these are just, these covers, some of these jackets are just magnificent.

32:59.397 --> 33:00.698
They look brand new, don't they, really?

33:00.718 --> 33:02.661
There's an addition in this book.

33:02.681 --> 33:05.665
The Land of the Mist?

33:06.978 --> 33:12.266
Even these later books, for instance, and large books, they all have jackets.

33:12.326 --> 33:19.076
They're all... Then there's, let's see, There's a Lost World.

